description: I supported a complex DOD intelligence system, the Tactical Exploitation System (TES) in multiple environments including hostile deployments. System included many flavors of UNIX (Solaris, Trusted Solaris, SGI Irix and HP Unix), Red hat Linux, and Windows servers. I was responsible for networking in strategic and tactical environments. My tasks included maintenance, upgrades, security, scripting, obtaining requirements and in-depth troubleshooting. I left this position for location preference, it was a very rewarding experience and my coworkers were of the highest caliber. The management was caring, incredibly competent and took very good care of their people.

description: Served as an imagery analyst and full motion video analyst in the Fox 1st AVN Regt TOC. Served as an analyst in the PACOM AOR. Served as Screener, Editor, Producer, and Analyst. Provided critical real-time intelligence support to forward-deployed coalition forces, which directly influenced field operations on counter terrorism issues using Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAV). Played a vital role in the safety and accomplishment of mission for these soldiers. Worked 300 missions, produces 2000+ graphics using SocketGXP and Microsoft Office for use in the field by coalition forces.

description: Served as an all-source analyst assigned to the Intelligence Assessment & Assistance Team (IAAT) at ISAF. Gathered performance data and user feedback on ISR Systems supporting the IC, with emphasis on the systems fielded as a result of ISR TF activities. Projects included quantitative and qualitative data collection and analysis of large volumes of system performance data in the context of ISR and military operations data. The results from these studies are a critical component of current understanding of ISR effectiveness. Data gathering and analysis efforts actively support other ongoing ISR TF assessments, including cross cutting ISR analysis’s and the ISR force sizing for IC activity.

Consistently used imagery to monitor trends and events on target location.

description: Served as an imagery analyst assigned to NSAs Project UNDERCUT. Provided GEOINT/IMINT support to the NTOC. The NSA Threat Operations center played a vital role in the diversity of the time-sensitive intelligence, warning, and response to global threats the U.S. Government information networks. Monitored facilities with the EUCOM AOR over an extended period, including trend analysis and events characterization. Utilized Remote View, AIMS, Intelink, Gemini, and other intelligence sources. Worked on a long term project that involved finding and identifying over 80 Cyber related facilities. Interacted and corresponded with other intelligence professionals within NGA and NSA to ensure the correct locations of these facilities. Provided expertise to NSA concerning NTM imagery collection and capabilities and helped them attain hardcopy and softcopy NTM and commercial imagery.

description: Provided time-sensitive imagery and geospatial products to multiple agencies within the Pentagon. Provided GEOINT/IMINT support to the NJOIC. Produced graphics daily that represented any and all major activities world-wide for that shift. Used Google Earth, Intelink, RemoteView, Microsoft Office Suite and other programs to ensure that briefs were well presented to the Deputy Director of Intelligence daily. Briefs included all activity and tracking that occurred during the shift. Use of Commercial Imagery to ensure products presented to customers met the needs of their projects. Provided standard NGA graphics to annotate facility changes observed within the AOR. Work on an HVT resulted in the production of at least one NGA First Look. Briefed intelligence officials on the watch floor about the uses of imagery within the IC and what an asset it is. Provided input about imagery analysis that was used in the Watch Desk Officer SOP.

description: Served as an imagery analyst and full motion video analyst in the NGA’S CTAAC-East. Served as an analyst in the CENTCOM and PACOM AOR. Served as Screener, Editor, Producer, and Team Lead. Provided critical real-time intelligence support to forward-deployed coalition forces, which directly influenced field operations on counter terrorism issues using Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAV). Played a vital role in the safety and accomplishment of mission for these soldiers. Worked 350 missions, exploited 3000 hours of airborne imagery data exploited using the MAAS workstations and software. Had daily impact directing on the ground forces to mission success. Collaborated with CENTCOM and PACOM intelligence and operations elements directly. Wrote custom reports, gave live commands over MIRC, and re-directed airborne/FMV collection on the fly to respond to action on the ground.

description: Provided time-sensitive imagery and geospatial products to multiple agencies within the Pentagon. Provided GEOINT/IMINT support to the NJOIC. Produced graphics daily that represented any and all major activities world-wide for that shift. description: Served as an imagery analyst and full motion video analyst in the NGA’S CTAAC-East. Served as an analyst in the CENTCOM and PACOM AOR. Served as Screener, Editor, Producer, and Team Lead. Provided critical real-time intelligence support to forward-deployed coalition forces, which directly influenced field operations on counter terrorism issues using Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAV). Played a vital role in the safety and accomplishment of mission for these soldiers. Worked 350 missions, exploited 3000 hours of airborne imagery data exploited using the MAAS workstations and software. Had daily impact directing on the ground forces to mission success. Collaborated with CENTCOM and PACOM intelligence and operations elements directly. Wrote custom reports, gave live commands over MIRC, and re-directed airborne/FMV collection on the fly to respond to action on the ground.

description: Served as a Geospatial and HUMINT analyst in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom while located in Baghdad, Iraq. Provided updated daily attacks and accident reports within the entire AO of Iraq. Provided daily reports based upon research on Iraqi Intelligence. Was the S2 NCOIC which included the daily responsibility of planning mission routes for the troops on ground in the unit. Updated SIGACTS daily and briefed the Brigade Commander as well and multiple Intelligence Officers located on Camp Victory, Iraq.

description: Served as the Knowledge Manager for the Theater Ground Intelligence Center – Central (TGIC-C) with an emphasis on intelligence data management and GEOINT architecture development and integration. Provided expert technical and analytical advice to the Director and Brigade Commander on matters relating to knowledge management (KM) in support of intelligence operations. Acted as the primary staff expert for the coordination and integration of all Distributed Common Ground System – Army (DCGS-A) systems and software. Enabled multi-discipline intelligence analysis, production, and collection management in support of ARCENTs full-spectrum operations in the CENTCOM AOR. Provided Subject Matter Expertise on GEOINT architecture and Processing, Exploitation and Dissemination (PED) in support of the establishment of the first INSCOM PED Center of Excellence at Fort Gordon.

description: Served as the GEOINT Chief for CJTF-1 in support of Operation Enduring Freedom (OEF). Managed geospatial and imagery intelligence systems, software, processing and production for the Senior Intelligence Officer (CJ2) to support the CJTF Commander’s Intelligence Requirements; provided direct support to targeting efforts and technical control of GEOINT systems. Served as IMINT Collection Manager ; coordinated with the National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (NGA), CENTCOM, IJC and USFOR-A for National, Theater and Tactical collection resources that enabled five U.S. Maneuver Brigade Combat Teams (BCTs), two International Maneuver Brigades and one U.S. Combat Aviation Brigade (CAB) in combat. Integrated and led a GEOINT section that included Airmen, Marines, Soldiers and NGA civilians; set the standard for GEOINT support in OEF. Provided oversight for all GEOINT foreign disclosure requirements; enabled a true coalition collaborative environment. A consummate professional that was consistently selected to brief Senior Intelligence Officers, Combat Commanders and distinguished visitors. Deployed and implemented a visualization capability within RC-East that enabled all users with access to data that directly supported the execution of all Warfighting Functions.

description: Responsible for all aspects of Geospatial Intelligence (GEOINT) within the 1st Cavalry Division (1CD). Developed, drafted and implemented the first GEOINT Cell Concept of Operations (CONOP) within the 1CD in preparation for an upcoming deployment to Afghanistan. Successfully consolidated all GEOINT capability and capacity within the Division Headquarters; provided increased efficiency and flexibility through a better application of existing resources. Leveraged the local Foundry site as the first “Reach Back” PED site on Fort Hood in support of OEF deployed GEOINT teams. Advised Command Staff, G2 leadership and subordinate Brigade S2s on training opportunities and established GEOINT training requirements for 1st Cavalry Division GEOINT cells. Provided professional mentorship to all GEOINT analysts within the Division and oversaw GEOINT specific deployment readiness training and professional development of all assigned NCOs and Soldiers.

description: Served as the Chief Instructor and Non-Commissioned Officer in Charge (NCOIC) of the U.S. Army GEOINT Exploitation Training Committee. Supervised the daily activities of 21 military and civilian team members involved in the creation, update, and presentation of GEOINT training materials. Developed future advanced GEOINT exploitation training strategies. Responsible for the accountability, operations, maintenance, and system administration of all computer-based training systems and equipment. Identified training gaps and shortfalls based on current Army GEOINT mission requirements. Transitioned a mostly Cold War focused course to a relevant Full Spectrum Operations GEOINT support curriculum. Integrated the Imagery Exploitation Support System (IESS) within all GEOINT courses at Fort Huachuca.

description: Directly supported world-wide Tomahawk Land Attack Missile (TLAM) mission planning. Maintained databases and developed procedures to validate accuracy of planned targeting missions. Served as National Imagery Collection Manager and Exploitation Lead, supervised a joint GEOINT cell that conducted imagery analysis in direct support of TLAM mission planning. Enabled unprecedented response time and accuracy during the largest TLAM strike ever conducted (375+) in support of the first military actions in Iraq as directed by the President of the United States. Provided vital GEOINT exploitation expertise to facilitate the targeting of 250 TLAM missions launched in support of OEF and OIF. Directly coordinated with NGA to Integrate the National Imagery Library (NIL), Command Imagery Library (CIL), Dissemination Element Client (DE-Client) and Imagery Exploitation Capability (IEC) to the CMSA imagery intelligence architecture.

description: Duty Postion: OPERATIONS SERGEANT (E7). Responsible for the operational management of protective services operations for the largest battalion in CID, comprised of 201 special agents in 4 executive-level protection detachments; prepares and manages operational plans and orders for high-risk missions in support of the Secretary of Defense, Deputy Secretary of Defense, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Secretary of the Army, Chief of Staff of the Army and their foreign counterparts visiting the United States; conducts battalion-level compliance inspections and Staff Assistance Visits for the 4 detachments. Additionally, served as the Unit liaison to Pentagon Force Protection Agency (PFPA), U.S. Secret Service (USSS), U.S. Capitol Police, DoD Technical Support Working Group (TSWG), and Federal Protective Services Working Group (FPSWG).
